Financial crisis in Europe exposed the weaknesses in Malta’s economy so in 2017 the indicators are far from optimistic. One in four 25-44 year old Maltese work in construction, and in 2008 our lowest-paid workers earned 2.2 times less than the 2128.00 euros per capita compensation in the European Union, the lowest among EU Member States. Gross domestic product (GDP) is the market value of all final goods and services from a nation in a given year. GDP data is commonly used to compare the productivity of a country over time or in comparison with the international economy.

Inflation was also a problem in Malta. Inflation reached a peak of nearly 5 per cent per year in 2008. People continued to borrow cheaply in foreign currency further leading to the crisis which dragged on for the following 15 years.
